WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.840
In this video, we'll be showing you the latest in RStudio 1.4 and how these features can

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:19.440
benefit you and your team for credible, agile, and durable data science results.

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:24.240
The Visual Editor is one of the more exciting new options, making working with code in RMarkdown

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:26.459
easier than ever.

00:00:26.459 --> 00:00:32.660
This new interface allows you to compose actual RMarkdown using the familiar visual interface.

00:00:32.660 --> 00:00:41.020
With it, you have easy access to format commands, inserting images, tables, just to name a few

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:46.139
of the options available in the visual pane.

00:00:46.139 --> 00:00:50.660
Continuing our theme for ease of use when authoring, you also have the ability to find

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:56.619
and insert citations from multiple sources, including integration with Zotero, a popular

00:00:56.619 --> 00:00:59.840
free and open-source reference manager.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:04.419
This not only makes the citation for you, but it also creates your bibliography, reducing

00:01:04.419 --> 00:01:08.900
the time spent in busy work while providing research.

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:14.379
Another thing we've spent quite a bit of time working on in RStudio 1.4 is Python, which

00:01:14.379 --> 00:01:19.620
we've focused more on in our latest releases.

00:01:19.620 --> 00:01:25.419
The largest feature now available is support for Python in the Environment pane.

00:01:25.419 --> 00:01:30.260
This allows you to switch directly between R mode and Python mode in that pane to look

00:01:30.260 --> 00:01:35.180
at data in different environments in R or immediately change the view to look at data

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:38.120
in different modules in Python.

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:44.919
We can browse these Python modules in the pane or open it to view directly in our workspace.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:49.519
This allows you to interact with data in Python in much the same way that you interact

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:52.199
with data in R.

00:01:52.199 --> 00:01:57.279
While RStudio is powered by R and will always be an R-first IDE, we will continue to work

00:01:57.279 --> 00:02:02.599
to improve the ability to use Python alongside it, allowing teams to mix these languages

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:04.879
to suit their needs.

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:09.399
In addition, Python environment selections are now available, allowing you to select

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:14.800
the version of Python you would like to use or switch between at any moment, or use in

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:16.839
each project.

00:02:16.839 --> 00:02:21.440
This is all powered by the reticulate package which enables these Python-based features

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:25.160
in RStudio 1.4.

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:29.460
Another new feature that many users are excited about are rainbow parentheses, which helps

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:33.679
you to more easily view and decipher different sections of your code.

00:02:33.679 --> 00:02:38.199
This ultimately aids in following deeply nested constructs, allowing you to view the different

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:42.880
levels and find the connected pairs.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:48.240
In addition, you can now use any monospace font you like to customize your coding experience,

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:52.160
allowing you to tailor the environment to your preference.

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:56.360
Mainly designed for widescreen monitors, we also provide the ability to have multiple

00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:00.440
source columns in the RStudio pane layout.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:04.139
This allows you to take advantage of any space you may have while avoiding the opening of

00:03:04.139 --> 00:03:08.160
endless windows on your screen.

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:13.619
Also new in RStudio 1.4 is the command palette, which allows you to invoke any RStudio command

00:03:13.619 --> 00:03:18.679
with just a few keystrokes, such as opening a new R Markdown document.

00:03:18.679 --> 00:03:23.279
This also allows you to very easily find and learn custom shortcuts that you can use in

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:27.639
your everyday work and increase your efficiency.

00:03:27.639 --> 00:03:31.839
One key feature that is available in both the open source and commercial server version

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:38.279
of RStudio IDE is the ability to customize where your data and configuration are stored

00:03:38.279 --> 00:03:41.559
for both the users and the servers.

00:03:41.559 --> 00:03:46.720
This opens up workflows for mounting configuration within containers, helping to solve the long

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:51.720
standing problem of users filling up their home directories and guiding content to where

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:54.919
it should appropriately go.

00:03:54.919 --> 00:03:58.679
Moving from the open source, let's also walk through the new features that are now available

00:03:58.839 --> 00:04:03.160
with the Pro Edition of RStudio 1.4.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:06.839
Undoubtedly the most requested and important of our recent additions is the ability to

00:04:06.839 --> 00:04:11.720
authenticate RStudio Server Pro now using SAML.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:17.760
This option along with Open IDE enables single sign-on for users and systems, with standardization

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:21.920
that provides fast yet reliable security.

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:25.799
In addition to load balancing with the local launcher, project sharing with the launcher

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:27.959
is also now available.

00:04:27.959 --> 00:04:31.839
Previously both of these popular features were not available to use at the same time,

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:37.880
but now even when you've launcherized an environment, you can still share your projects with others.

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:42.320
While it still requires some setup for permissions, these are both big features with the commercial

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:48.679
server version of RStudio IDE that are now available to use at the same time.

00:04:48.679 --> 00:04:54.040
Of note for those who need to request a GPU with SLURM, this is now possible with custom

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:57.640
SBatch parameters.

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:02.200
Another nice new feature for the commercial server version of the RStudio IDE is the ability

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:05.320
to run Visual Studio Code sessions.

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:10.119
This is currently in beta and is great for those who want to run longer form Python programs

00:05:10.119 --> 00:05:14.480
while working with other teams and projects within the RStudio Server environment.

